<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-396-186  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 396 186.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  May 1 1990 v4 n17 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Gates spells out Microsoft strategy. (Microsoft Corp Chairman andCEO Bill Gates announces major upgrades to Microsoft applicationsafter Apple introduces System 7.0)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cohen, Raines.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Microsoft Corp Chmn and CEO Bill Gates states that the companyplans major upgrades to its Mac applications following the releaseof Apple's System 7.0 operating system software.andP;  Gates told theNational Apple Users Group Conference, in Apr 1990, that a futureversion of the Excel spreadsheet will incorporate advancedgraphing, macro, and layering functions, and that the Word wordprocessor will support compound document architectures.andP;  Theintegrated Microsoft Works package will feature improvedintegration, communications, and charting capabilities, and thePowerPoint presentation package will feature animation and specialinteractive effects.andP;  Gates says that revising applications forSystem 7.0 creates dilemmas for developers because newcategory-specific features are difficult to test.andP;  He also expectsan emphasis on client/server computing and object-orienteddevelopment tools in the 1990s.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (planning).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Topic:     Strategic PlanningProduct DevelopmentUpgradingConferencesSoftware Packages.andO;Person:    Gates, William H. (addresses, essays, lectures).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Raines CohenandM;Arlington Heights, Ill.andP;  -- Users can expect major upgrades to many Microsoftapplications soon after Apple ships System 7.0, according to Microsoft Corp.andO;Chairman and CEO Bill Gates.andM;Speaking before the Nation-al Apple Users Group Conference here last month,Gates described Microsoft's upgrade strategy for its Macintosh applications:andM;andgt;Excel.andP;  Gates promised a major upgrade incorporating advanced graphing andmacro functions, as well as layering.andP;  &quot;Think of the spreadsheet as anoutline where you can zoom in and out on your data.andP;  You need to consolidateinformation from multiple files, with the program acting as a smartadministrative assistant and automatically recognizing the structure of yourdata,&quot; he explained.andM;andgt;Word.andP;  &quot;What we really need in word processors,&quot; he said, &quot;is anarchitecture where any kind of data can be brought in, be it im-age, voicedata or whatever.andP;  The full realization of compound-document architecture isto be able to add new types without going back to the manufacturer.&quot; Gatesalso promised embedded drawing capabilities and faster display of text.andM;andgt;Works.andP;  Users can expect improved integration, charting and communicationscapabilities, the Microsoft chief said.andM;andgt;Mail.andP;  &quot;It's a more fundamental application than people think,&quot; Gates said.andO;In the future, &quot;group productivity products with functions such as bulletinboarding, indexing and viewing&quot; will be built on top of Microsoft Mail, hepredicted.andM;andgt;PowerPoint.andP;  New versions will feature special effects, animation andinteractivity, Gates said.andM;Gates described the dilemmas developers face when revising applications forSystem 7, which may not be released to the public until January 1991.andP;  &quot;It iskind of tricky, from a testing perspective, deciding whether to add newcategory-specific features in an upgrade before or after the new system,&quot; hesaid.andP;  &quot;Most of our new revisions will be coming out right after System 7 isreleased.&quot;andM;But Gates addressed a number of issues beyond upgrades to existing software.andO;New products under development at Microsoft include multimedia informationapplications as well as productivity titles on CD-ROM, he said.andP;  &quot;Having theprogram, documentation, examples and everything you need on a CD-ROM is, Ithink, as dramatic as moving from a character-based to a graphical interface.andO;Microsoft is investing very heavily.&quot;andM;Gates also described his view of computing in the 1990s, emphasizingclient-server computing; graphical user interfaces; object-orienteddevelopment tools and information browsers; and smaller, specializedapplications that rely extensively on interapplication communications.andM;Microsoft and Apple are collaborating on several advanced technologies andstrategic projects, he said.andP;  &quot;In fact, I spent some time with John Sculleyin the past few months, so Apple can focus on advances as important as theMacintosh was for us in 1984,&quot; he said.andP;  One probable area for jointresearch, he said, is handwriting recognition.andP;  He cautioned that usableproducts incorporating the technology are more than two years away, but hecalled it &quot;far easier than voice recognition.&quot;andM;Gates also took the unusual position that Microsoft Windows will benefitMacintosh users.andP;  &quot;We have this very positive dynamic where the higher-volumestandard, MS-DOS, has stayed behind in terms of advanced user interface,&quot; hesaid.andP;  &quot;As [DOS] improves, Apple has to take risks and innovate with advancessuch as object-oriented environments, multimedia and lower prices.&quot; n</TEXT></DOC>